    "html": "<section class=\"catalog-card-content\" data-source-problem=\"Math Note\" data-source-type=\"Math Note\">\n<div class=\"problem-body\">\n\n<p><strong>Area, Rectangles, and Square Units</strong></p>\n<p>To find the <strong>area of a rectangle</strong>, choose a conveniently sized square unit to cover the rectangle exactly with no overlaps. Sometimes parts of square units are needed to cover the rectangle completely.</p>\n<p>In the rectangle shown below, using squares with side lengths of one foot, it takes $18$ squares to cover the rectangle. Therefore, the area of the rectangle is $18$ square feet.</p>\n<p>One way to count squares in a rectangle quickly is to multiply the lengths of two sides that meet at a corner, since multiplication is defined as repeated addition. For example, the region of the rectangle can be seen as either six groups of three squares or three groups of six squares. In either case, the area of a rectangle can be computed using:</p>\n<p class=\"mathline\">$A = (\\text{length})(\\text{width})$</p>\n<p>The same-sized shape may appear to have different areas if it is measured using different units of measure. The area did not change, but the number of different-sized units did. In the second rectangle shown below, the rectangle is measured in yards instead of feet.</p>\n<div class=\"figures\"><img alt=\"Rectangle measured as 6 feet by 3 feet with square foot grid\" src=\"assets/lesson_2_2_3/math-note-rectangle-feet.png\"/><img alt=\"Same rectangle measured as 2 yards by 1 yard with square yard grid\" src=\"assets/lesson_2_2_3/math-note-rectangle-yards.png\"/></div>\n\n</div>\n</section>",
    "assets": [
      "assets/lesson_2_2_3/math-note-rectangle-feet.png",
      "assets/lesson_2_2_3/math-note-rectangle-yards.png"
    ],
